Our rider volume data is created by the Strava cycling mobile app. In our current configuration, these volume lines indicate places people have had their tracking turned on in their mobile phones. Although the intention of the app is to just track bike rides, it's very possible and probably that some of the data is incorrect due to people leaving the app on accidentally, etc. Currently, we're just aiming to collect incident, hazard, and theft locations and information. The volume data is provided more so for visualization purposes so everyone can get an idea of places people are riding the more or less.

Our rider volume data is created by the Strava cycling mobile app. In our current configuration, the volume data indicates places people had the tracking turned on in their mobile phones. It's very possible (and probable) that some of the data is incorrect as a result of people leaving the app on accidentally, etc. BikeMaps is currently aiming to just collect incident, hazard, and theft information while the volume data is provided for visualization purposes and to give a general idea of the places people are riding.

fields.comment:
All the fields that are required to submit a report are marked by an asterisk. These fields are the minimum amount of information we need to analyze the data in a meaningful way. If you do fill out the additional fields, this information is also stored and we may be able to do some interesting additional analysis with it, as well as display it to the public in the future. 
The description of the event is not required, but it may be useful to give some extra details to help us improve our form or to provide a personal account of what happened should we make this data visible to the public in the future. It is likely that this feature will be implemented.

fields.comment:
Hello Bel.on.Wheels,

Changing the details of any reported information isn't currently possible. This is because the nature of our privacy terms prevent us from attaching any identifying information to reports. We can change this for you manually if you either send me a private message or use the contact link on the about page and provide any information about the point you can (displayed time, kind of incident, any description you may have filled out) as well as the correct time that it should be. 

I should also mention that we were experiencing some temporary issues with the way date and time was displayed yesterday (It was displaying the UTC time rather than local times). Be sure to check the point you reported, as the problem may have resolved itself with that bug fix.

Thanks, 
Taylor Denouden
taylor@bikemaps.org

fields.comment:
Very cool map.  This will come in helpful when riding in new cities.

A neat feature would be to have a 'bicyclist preferred route'.  It might be shorter, flatter, safer, more scenic, or some other reason.  There is one road near me that Stratva says more people ride on, but the cars drive 50 mph and there is a 3 inch shoulder.  Right next to the road 1/10th of a mile away is a quiet residential road that goes to the same place.  I can mark the one bad road with a green? cyclist hazard marker, but there isn't a way to show the best way to go.  And in turn give it some credibility to have the city put up signs or paint a line on the road for bicyclists to follow to stay safe.

Is there some way to get the bike trail and dedicated bike lane information that Google has?   It is pretty obvious where they are from the number of riders in the big cities, but when they are in small towns they don't get as many people riding them and don't show up.  We are also building a lot of them and connecting them around Ohio.

We have 'bike highways' across the US, it would be cool if these routes were overlaid so you could see the best route in rural areas that don't get as much bike traffic.  http://www.adventurecycling.org/routes-and-maps/us-bicycle-route-system/

Marking where bike repair stores are on the map would also be helpful.  Both full ones like a local bike shop and partial ones like Wal-Mart that have tubes and small parts.

fields.comment:
I live in Vancouver and noticed right away that pretty much all the intersections with a large number of incidents are locations where a major bike route crosses a primary motor-vehicle thoroughfare. While interesting, this would probably be easy to guess -- some of those routes get thousands of bikes per day, as supported by your rider volume data.

I wonder if it may be instructive to discover areas that have a large number of incidents relative to the volume of cyclists.

Wonderful site! Thank you!

fields.comment:
I do bicycling advocacy work in Santa Cruz County, California. One of the mapping tools I use is the [Transportation Injury Mapping System (TIMS)](http://tims.berkeley.edu/). It uses California Highway Patrol data from the Statewide Injury Traffic Reporting System (SWITRS) and allows export of data.

Is there a way to import this data into BikeMaps.org?

I used another tool to create [maps of bicyclist and pedestrian injuries from 2003-2013 along the most dangerous road in our county](https://stevepiercy.cartodb.com/viz/6a1d4b6e-ac4a-11e4-90c3-0e4fddd5de28/public_map) by importing SWITRS data, but it would require some hefty programming to create an interface that would allow users to record incidents, like BikeMaps.org allows. I'd love to be able to combine features of BikeMaps.org with CartoDB.com.

fields.comment: FYI, there is a layer in [OpenStreetsMap called Cycle Map](http://www.openstreetmap.org/#map=16/36.9738/-121.9646&layers=C) for entering bicycling infrastructure via crowdsourcing. Bike racks in the map at that link appear as tiny blue squares. Perhaps you could query that layer?
